{
  "title": "ok! I made some notes here in @brainstorm for four sketches - thoughts on creati",
  "messages": [
    {
      "content": "ok! I made some notes here in @brainstorm for four sketches - thoughts on creating these? my sense is we should have the skeletons of these created and maybe come up with better titles - what other context do you need?\n[References: @note:brainstorm.md]",
      "role": "user"
    },
    {
      "content": "nice - the audience in this case is *mixed* - my sense is there will be more business decision makers and technical decision makers but also developers. I like a technical style. For the actual app, here's some of the previous beats:\nA competitor announces a superior allergy treatment drug launching in November — putting our market position at risk\nThe business rapidly mobilizes a small, agile, cross-functional team to assess the impact and accelerate our superior next-gen product to defend share and unlock incremental revenue\nPersonas: Project manager as ringleader, Operations Lead as 2nd team member\nPhase 1 – Assess the impact and build the case: gather data and quantify the opportunity\nPhase 2 – Validate the constraints and model the new scenario: supply chain limits the accelerated window -> agents can help!\nPhase 3 – Build the proposal and present to leadership: and recommend autonomous supply chain agents to hit the timeline\nUsing the Operations BRD, an IT business analyst builds an  autonomous Production Planning agent in Copilot Studio that integrates directly into the team's daily collaboration workspace.\nConnected to Work IQ and D365 ERP, the agent aggregates data across three plants to assess capacity, materials, and equipment constraints.\nIt proactively alerts the team with optimized run orders that rebalance volume and compress changeover times and runs a what-if analysis modeling the scenario and returning an executable plan with risks flagged for human acceptance.\nThe team reviews with a one-click, multi-agent sign-off, audited in Dataverse and governed by Agent 365, turning a slow, manual process into a continuous execution loop and leaving a full specification the development team can build on to create our organizations fleet of Agents.\n[Our beat - but our narrative is better]\nBuild a fleet of agents to improve supply chain operations - inventory, out‑of‑stock, availability‑to‑promise\nStarting in GitHub Copilot App, bring in an existing app from Copilot Studio (TBD)\nGitHub Copilot App runs multiple agent sessions, all in parallel, managing their own review cycles. Agents orchestrate the entire software lifecycle\nUsing Foundry, I select a model tuned specifically to our supply chain operations, processes and patterns — using Frontier Tuning, connect to my knowledge base and deploy to production\nWith Microsoft IQ, my supply chain agents return insights grounded in internal knowledge & external context, actively improving supply chain operations to launch ahead of the competition\nAgents operate as an extension of our teams, fully integrated into the flow of work, actively engaging in Microsoft Teams and M365.\nSecurity plays an active role in the SDLC loop. Code is scanned, exploits proven in a sandbox, findings flow back to the developer as a Copilot PR: Found, proven, fixed before the agent ships.\n[After our beat]\nIn Defender, the new vulnerability in MDASH is recorded in the Red-team agent in Perception and deeper internal investigation begins across similar repos.\nIn the same Defender console. new threat intelligence reports   a new attack pattern targeting supply agents,. With a human in the loop, project Perception's security agents take action against the threat and make the correction.\n<Include bridge> In A365 - Security admin reviews the supply chain agent now live in production and no attack has occurred.  They reside alongside the rest of the agent fleet. Governance, policy(healthcare), and healthcare posture are green\nA365 - Agents run securely on Windows 11/Scout with OS enforced identity, containment(MXC) and enterprise-grade manageability. A365 control plane extends to Windows and agents can be observed and governed  similar to in cloud environments.",
      "role": "user"
    },
    {
      "content": "Because I over-structured it.\n\nI used **Part 1A / 1B / 1C / 1D** to signal that these four sketches all belong to the same larger section, but that is probably too heavy for sketch titles.\n\nFor working sketches, that naming can feel:\n- too formal\n- too presentation-like\n- a little confusing if these are just sequential scenes inside one part\n\nA cleaner model is usually:\n\n- the **storyboard** carries the part name\n- the **sketches** carry simple scene names\n\nSo instead of:\n\n- Part 1A - Triage the Response in GitHub Copilot App\n- Part 1B - Promote the Agent from Local to Cloud\n- Part 1C - Improve the Agent\n- Part 1D - Govern the Agent and Hand Off to Protection\n\nyou'd likely want:\n\n- **Triage in GitHub Copilot App**\n- **Promote the Agent to Cloud**\n- **Improve the Agent**\n- **Govern the Agent Fleet**\n\nThen the storyboard or enclosing sequence can be named something like:\n\n- **Part 1 - Build and Operationalize the Supply Chain Agent**\n- or\n- **Part 1 - From Triage to Governed Agent**\n\nSo the short answer is: I was trying to make the hierarchy explicit, but I put that hierarchy in the wrong place.\n\nIf you want, I can fix this now by:\n1. removing the **Part 1A/1B/1C/1D** prefixes from the sketch titles, and\n2. optionally creating a **single storyboard** that carries the Part 1 label.",
      "role": "assistant"
    },
    {
      "content": "yes - lets do it",
      "role": "user"
    },
    {
      "content": null,
