    {
      "content": "Done.\n\n## New sketch titles\n- **Triage in GitHub Copilot App**\n- **Promote the Agent to the Cloud**\n- **Improve the Agent**\n- **Govern the Agent Fleet**\n\n## What I changed\n- Removed the `Part 1A/1B/1C/1D` naming\n- Kept the existing row structure intact\n- Updated each sketch description so it reads cleanly on its own, while still fitting into a larger three-part arc\n\n## Why these titles work better\n- Short and clear\n- Easy to scan in a storyboard\n- Descriptive without sounding like final slide titles\n- They preserve the sequence:\n  - orient in app\n  - build and promote\n  - improve\n  - govern and hand off\n\nIf you want, next I can:\n- create the **storyboard** for this section, or\n- tighten the titles even further into a more technical style, like:\n  - `App Triage`\n  - `Local to Cloud`\n  - `Agent Improvement`\n  - `Fleet Governance`",
      "role": "assistant"
    },
    {
      "content": "can we move to having bullet points instead of concrete narratives? i think you also figured this collection of sketches encompased the whole thing - its only one part of three",
      "role": "user"
    },
    {
      "content": "Yes - I think that is the stronger framing.\n\nRight now, the first sketch can read a little like \"here is GitHub Copilot App.\" What you actually want is:\n\n- **we already have a portfolio of internal apps**\n- **the market changed**\n- **we need to adapt one or more apps quickly**\n- **GitHub Copilot App is where the team figures out what to change and starts the work**\n\nThat gives the demo a much better reason to exist.\n\n## Why this framing is better\nIt shifts the story from:\n- \"look at this app\"\n\nto:\n- \"here is a real software response to a business problem\"\n\nThat helps with a mixed audience because:\n- **business decision makers** see urgency, portfolio impact, and prioritization\n- **technical decision makers** see software modernization and delivery motion\n- **developers** see where the actual work starts\n\nIt also gives you permission to stay focused on the **functional parts**:\n- what apps exist\n- which app or service needs to change\n- what agent gets introduced\n- how the team moves from assessment to build\n\n## Recommended framing for Sketch 1\nI would position Sketch 1 as:\n\n- We have an existing set of supply chain and operations apps\n- A competitor move forces a fast response\n- The question is not \"should we build an agent?\"\n- The question is \"where in this app estate do we add agent behavior first?\"\n- GitHub Copilot App helps the team triage that quickly and turn it into an actual development path\n\n## What that means for the first sketch\nInstead of a broad product tour, the beats should probably become:\n\n### 1. Set the business trigger\n- competitor launch changes the timeline\n- we need to protect share\n- the response has to happen in software we already own\n\n### 2. Show the app estate\n- portfolio of existing internal apps or services\n- likely candidates across supply chain, planning, inventory, availability-to-promise\n- identify where the bottleneck or opportunity is\n\n### 3. Narrow to one active initiative\n- choose the app or service to extend\n- explain why this is the highest-leverage place to add agent behavior\n- connect it to the operations team and project lead\n\n### 4. Use GitHub Copilot App to organize the work\n- open the active repo, worktree, session, canvas\n- show that the team is moving from discussion to implementation\n- keep the emphasis on triage and decomposition\n\n### 5. End with the build target\n- the Production Planning agent\n- or the skill / service / integration that becomes the first concrete addition\n- then hand off into local development in Sketch 2\n\n## Suggested title refinements\nYour current title is fine, but if you want the title to reflect this better, I would consider:\n\n- **Triage the App Portfolio**\n- **Choose Where Agents Fit**\n- **Plan the Agentic Update**\n- **Triage the Supply Chain Apps**\n- **Find the First Agentic Insert**\n\nMy favorite if you want a technical-business balance:\n\n- **Triage the App Portfolio**\n\nor, if you want it more concrete:\n\n- **Choose the First Agentic Update**\n\n## My recommendation\nFor this demo, I would make Sketch 1 less about navigation chrome and more about:\n\n- app portfolio\n- active project\n- prioritization\n- selecting the first agentic change\n\nThen use GitHub Copilot App as the place where that decision becomes executable.\n\n## Context I would still want from you\nTo tighten Sketch 1, the most useful missing inputs are:\n\n- the **3-5 apps** in the portfolio you want to reference\n- which **one app** becomes the main focus\n- whether the Production Planning agent is:\n  - a new standalone agent,\n  - a Copilot Studio agent brought into the app,\n  - or a skill/service added into an existing app\n- how literal you want the repo/app mapping to be:\n  - one app, one repo\n  - one platform, multiple services\n  - mixed portfolio\n- whether you want the first sketch to feel more like:\n  - **portfolio triage**, or\n  - **repo triage inside one chosen app**\n\n## Best next move\nI suggest I rewrite **Sketch 1** around this exact framing in bullet form:\n- existing app estate\n- urgent market trigger\n- choose the first app to update\n- identify the Production Planning agent as the implementation target\n\nIf you want, I can update the first sketch now and also rename it to something closer to **Triage the App Portfolio**.",
      "role": "assistant"
    },
