      "content": "Updated **Triage in GitHub Copilot App**.\n\n## What changed\nI shifted the first sketch away from a product tour and toward:\n- an existing **portfolio of internal apps**\n- a **market trigger**\n- a quick **triage decision**\n- selection of the **first agentic update**\n\n## Why this is better\nIt makes GitHub Copilot App the place where the team:\n- assesses the app estate\n- chooses where to act\n- turns that decision into implementation work\n\nSo the sketch now supports the functional story you want, instead of feeling like a navigation walkthrough.\n\n## What I changed in the rows\n- **Row 0** now frames the company as already operating multiple internal apps\n- **Row 1** keeps GitHub Copilot App visible, but positions it as a control surface\n- **Row 2** now focuses on reviewing the app collection and choosing the highest-value insertion point\n- **Row 3** turns the tool features into triage and scoping mechanisms\n- **Row 4** still lands on the Production Planning agent as the handoff into code\n\n## One thing I would refine next\nIf you want this sketch to feel even more concrete, the biggest upgrade would be to name the actual app portfolio in Row 2. For example:\n- demand planning\n- production planning\n- inventory allocation\n- supplier coordination\n- plant scheduling\n\nThat would make the decision point feel much more real.\n\nIf you want, I can do one more pass on Sketch 1 and make the app portfolio more explicit with 3 to 5 named apps.",
